        >
          Full backstory, construction, legend and later history of Buenos Aires' most famous stepped skyscraper.
        </p>
      </header>

      <article class="article language-panel" lang="en" data-language-panel="en">
        <section id="bottom-line" aria-labelledby="bottom-line-heading">
          <h2 id="bottom-line-heading">Bottom line</h2>
          <p>
            Edificio Kavanagh is a stepped residential skyscraper in Retiro, Buenos Aires, at Florida 1065 facing Plaza San Martín. Commissioned by <a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corina_Kavanagh" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Corina "Cora" Kavanagh</a> and built from 1934 to 1936, it was planned as a luxury rental tower (<em>edificio de renta</em>) and became one of the city's best-known modern buildings. Its triangular lot, reinforced-concrete structure and terraced profile made it a landmark of 1930s Buenos Aires. One reported construction-cost estimate is 5,000,000 pesos moneda nacional, about US$1.41M at a 1936 exchange rate of 3.55 pesos per dollar, or roughly US$350M in 2026 dollars if scaled as the same share of Argentina's GDP.
          </p>
          <p>
            Part of its fame comes from the stories attached to it. The most repeated version says Corina built the tower out of spite after the Anchorena family rejected a romance, placing it where it would block the view from their palace to the Basílica del Santísimo Sacramento. Other retellings turn her into the building's architect, or shift the romance to a daughter she did not have.
          </p>
          <p>
            The records point to a less theatrical history. Corina commissioned and financed the project, but the design is attributed to the studio of Sánchez, Lagos y de la Torre: the Uruguayan architect Gregorio Sánchez (1881–1941), engineer Ernesto Lagos (1890–1977) and Luis María de la Torre (1890–1975). The view-blocking effect is real; the romantic-revenge motive is weakly documented, contradicted by chronology and best treated as urban legend.
          </p>
          <blockquote>
            <p>
              <em>The main source here is chapter VII of Leonel Hernán Contreras' <cite>Rascacielos Porteños</cite> (2006), a detailed history of the Kavanagh building and its legends. I cite it below as Contreras (2006), and flag places where press or tourism sources give different versions.</em>
            </p>
          </blockquote>
          <p>
            Construction was led by the firm of engineer Rodolfo Cervini (Empresa Constructora Rodolfo Cervini S.A.). The reinforced-concrete structure went to Empresa Argentina de Cemento Armado (E.A.C.A.), based on a preliminary project by structural engineer Carlos Laucher and final calculations by E.A.C.A.'s Fernando Schwarz. Schwarz had to design what was then the world's tallest concrete skeleton at a time when wind-load and soil-mechanics engineering were still young fields (Contreras, <em>Rascacielos Porteños</em>, ch. VII; Nougués, 2023). Buenos Aires tourism itself presents the revenge story as legend, not confirmed fact (<a href="https://turismo.buenosaires.gob.ar/es/otros-establecimientos/edificio-kavanagh" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Turismo BA</a>).
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="cora-kavanagh" aria-labelledby="cora-kavanagh-heading">
          <h2 id="cora-kavanagh-heading">Who Corina "Cora" Kavanagh was</h2>
          <p>
            Corina Kavanagh (Buenos Aires, 20 February 1890 – 18 February 1984) was born into a wealthy Irish-Argentine family, though not one of Buenos Aires' old patrician clans. Elite society treated families like hers as "nuevos ricos," or new money (<a href="https://www.archdaily.com/1001110/the-story-of-cora-kavanagh-and-her-emblematic-building-in-buenos-aires" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">ArchDaily</a>). She was the eldest child of Irish immigrants John Patrick Kavanagh and Elisa Lynch Byrne, whose families came from rural Ireland: Ballygarrett, a village in County Wexford, and County Westmeath. She had one brother, Diego. Her money came from inherited land around Venado Tuerto, Santa Fe. To finance the tower, she sold estancias, large rural estates, there without taking bank loans. Sources disagree on whether she sold two or three (<a href="https://www.lanacion.com.ar/cultura/los-secretos-del-kavanagh-el-primer-edificio-moderno-de-buenos-aires-nid2139269/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">La Nación: Los secretos del Kavanagh</a>).
          </p>
          <p>
            Her private life was unsettled. She married three times, and none of those marriages seems to have been happy. The first was arranged: on 20 July 1912, when she was 22, she married Guillermo Ham Kenny, a millionaire Irish-Argentine landowner older than her father. They had no children and spent much of the next sixteen years in Europe, where she bought French antiques, haute couture from Paquin and Schiaparelli, and jewellery from Van Cleef and Boivin. Ham Kenny's death left her wealthier still.
          </p>
          <p>
            Her second husband was Carlos (or Guillermo) Mainini Ríos, the tuberculosis specialist who had treated Ham Kenny while he was dying. Corina met him in Paris around August 1929. The Vatican annulled the marriage about six years later. On 17 March 1938, she married Héctor Gustavo Casares Lynch, a patrician whose father had helped found the Jockey Club. She remained childless.
          </p>
          <p>
            She was a society figure and antiques collector. She appeared on the Christmas 1935 cover of <cite>Caras y Caretas</cite> and was painted by the society portraitist <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philip_de_L%C3%A1szl%C3%B3" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Philip de László</a>. She kept a French-style residence, "Palacio Kavanagh," in Olivos and later a mansion in Martínez.
          </p>
          <p>
            In the Kavanagh building, she reserved the entire 14th-floor apartment, 14 A, for herself: about 700 m², with its own terraces. Sources disagree on whether she really lived there long-term. After her rental income collapsed, she moved to smaller units in wing C, 6 C and 7 C, where she lived until her death in 1984, two days before turning 94. She is buried in Recoleta (<a href="https://bulletinofadvancedspanish.com/the-marvellous-miss-kavanagh-revenge-and-skyscrapers-in-buenos-aires/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Bulletin of Advanced Spanish</a>).
          </p>
          <p>
            Recent accounts move away from the image of Corina as a jilted romantic. They present her instead as an under-credited female patron of avant-garde 1930s architecture and as one of the city's first female real-estate developers. Marcelo Nougués makes that case in <cite>Cora Kavanagh y su edificio</cite> (Díaz Ortiz Ediciones, 2023; 572 pp.; ISBN 978-987-88-8094-5; with an English-translation appendix and a prologue by Ernesto Montequin; held at the CPAU library in Buenos Aires). The biography treats the revenge tale as folklore and reconstructs Corina's life, travels and art collecting from primary documents.
          </p>
          <p>
            Nougués also notes that almost no letters, interviews or direct testimony from Corina survive. What remains in oral tradition is mainly the "adulterated version" of the Anchorena romance (<a href="https://www.archdaily.com/1001110/the-story-of-cora-kavanagh-and-her-emblematic-building-in-buenos-aires" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">ArchDaily</a>).
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="why-built" aria-labelledby="why-built-heading">
          <h2 id="why-built-heading">Why it was built</h2>
          <p>
            The documented reason was a private rental-development project, or <em>edificio de renta</em>, meant to recover most of the capital invested. Around 1933 Corina, described as an eccentric young <em>estanciera</em>, or rural landowner, fascinated by everything avant-garde, decided to sell rural holdings to build it. Contreras says two estancias; Nougués and later press accounts say three. Her stated plan was to rent the apartments to wealthy young Buenos Aires families, among the few groups still able to afford them after the economic crisis.
          </p>
          <p>
            Some accounts credit the idea not to Corina but to her lawyers, Diego Garret Kavanagh and Pablo Cárdenas. They were the clients for whom the Sánchez–Lagos–de la Torre studio had built an earlier stepped building at Córdoba and Libertad in 1931, a project that prefigured the Kavanagh's silhouette (Contreras 2006). Before Argentina's horizontal-property regime normalized condominium ownership, towers like this usually had one owner and many tenants, generating long-term income. La Nación separately frames the Kavanagh as a rare case where municipal rules, private capital and a determined patron aligned, quoting Silvio Plotquin on how women like Corina promoted avant-garde 1930s projects without getting much credit for it (<a href="https://www.lanacion.com.ar/cultura/los-secretos-del-kavanagh-el-primer-edificio-moderno-de-buenos-aires-nid2139269/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">La Nación: Los secretos del Kavanagh</a>).
          </p>
          <p>
            The site mattered. The triangular lot at Florida and San Martín belonged to Carlos Alfredo Tornquist (son of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ernesto_Tornquist" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Ernesto Tornquist</a>), who had once planned to extend the neighbouring Plaza Hotel across the whole block. The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infamous_Decade" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">1930 crisis</a> killed that plan, and he sold the parcel to Corina (Contreras 2006). Plaza San Martín was one of the city's aristocratic stages, bordered by Anchorena, Paz, Ortiz Basualdo, the Plaza Hotel and Retiro Station.
          </p>
          <p>
            The municipality's Comisión de Estética Edilicia, the city Building Aesthetics Commission, had marked this spot as the "great gateway to the city," with the Retiro rail terminals just below the bluff. That civic plan helps explain why the city allowed the Kavanagh to rise to full skyscraper height in exchange for a ~10 m semi-public transverse street between the Plaza Hotel and the new tower (Contreras 2006). Argentina's heritage office describes the result as a luxury concrete <em>paquebote</em> (ocean-liner mass) inserted into that upper-class setting, tied to a modern American catalogue of comfort and technology: Westinghouse, Carrier and Otis (<a href="https://www.argentina.gob.ar/capital-humano/cultura/monumentos/edificio-kavanagh" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Argentina.gob.ar</a>). Rosa Aboy's academic work places it within a broader shift after the 1929 crash, from European mansion-style living toward modern high-rise apartments for the elite (<a href="https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/02665433.2012.629809" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Aboy, <cite>The right to a home?</cite></a>).
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="how-built" aria-labelledby="how-built-heading">
          <h2 id="how-built-heading">How it was built</h2>
          <p>
            Contreras gives a tight construction timeline. The demolition of the existing structures was auctioned on 24 June 1933, and the site was cleared by late August. Structural work began in January 1934, though the state heritage office dates the start to April 1934, after clearing. Concrete-pouring finished on 28 October 1934; by then the Kavanagh had overtaken São Paulo's Edifício Martinelli as the tallest reinforced-concrete structure in the world. The whole build took about 20 months, ending 30 September 1935, and the building was officially inaugurated on 15 January 1936. A reported construction-cost estimate is 5,000,000 pesos moneda nacional; at about PMN 3.55 per US$1 in 1936, that was roughly US$1.41M then. Scaled as the same share of Argentina's economy, about 0.0509% of GDP, it is about US$350M in 2026 dollars. The taxes paid on it (~180,000 pesos moneda nacional) were the highest ever paid for a building in Argentina to that date.
          </p>
          <p>
            The height figures vary less than they seem. Contreras gives ~110 m to the roof and 120.35 m to the top of the mast, with 30 high floors (a national record, and the first Argentine building to reach that many levels) plus a rooftop <em>mirador</em>, or lookout, sometimes counted as a 31st. At completion it was the tallest building in Argentina and Latin America, surpassing the Palacio Barolo, the SAFICO and even the 106 m towers of the Basilica of Luján (Contreras 2006). During the October 1934 Eucharistic Congress, a giant cross was mounted on the summit façade.
          </p>
          <p>
            The stepped, terraced form was practical as well as aesthetic. The building had to fit a complex triangular lot (~2,400 m²), so it was composed of five joined volumes: one central volume, flanked by two, then two smaller again. That arrangement gave it a symmetrical, ziggurat-like silhouette often read as a ship's prow pointed toward the Río de la Plata. Municipal height and setback rules, similar in spirit to New York's 1916 Zoning Resolution, shaped the massing. The setbacks created large garden terraces for about a third of the units. Unusually for Rationalist work, the building also uses the natural slope of the Plaza San Martín ravine rather than pretending the site is flat (<a href="https://modernabuenosaires.org/obras/20s-a-70s/kavanagh" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Moderna Buenos Aires</a>; Nougués, 2023).
          </p>
          <p>
            Critic Jorge Francisco Liernur reads it as "a perfect hybrid," reconciling program with building code, immediate context with urban scale and technological ambition with artisanal execution (Contreras 2006). La Nación's Fabio Grementieri called it a masterful synthesis of Rationalism and Art Deco, renewal and tradition, Paris and New York.
          </p>
          <p>
            The engineering figures were large for the era (Contreras 2006, citing the April 1936 special issue of <cite>Nuestra Arquitectura</cite>): 1,500 drawings for 25,800 m² of built area; 1,600 km of iron reinforcing bar; ~90 km of combined water, steam, drainage and electrical conduit; an electrical installation equivalent to powering a city of 80,000; and an air-conditioning refrigeration plant (the first central A/C in the world in a building of this type) capable of making ice for 75,000 people. Up to 613 workers a day were on site; 23,260 tonnes of materials required 5,000 truck trips; the structure was rated to bear ~31,000 tonnes.
          </p>
          <p>
            The interiors were just as technically ambitious. Apartments had electric kitchens (Nougués specifies 105 Hotpoint electric kitchens, 109 General Electric refrigerators and marble baths with coloured Standard sanitary ware), stainless-steel finishes, linoleum floors, Slavonian-oak parquet, cedar-and-okoumé wardrobe fittings and a dedicated automatic central telephone exchange wired to the public network. Even refrigerator electricity was included in the rent. Sanitary fittings ran to nearly 300 bathtubs (many custom-made), 120 washbasins, 370 valve-toilets, 235 bidets and 250 porcelain lavatories (Contreras 2006). The central hall held 12 high-speed elevators, with 200 stops total, behind a revolving door and marble staircase; private landings had oak <em>boiserie</em>, or decorative wood paneling, and leather armchairs (<a href="https://turismo.buenosaires.gob.ar/es/otros-establecimientos/edificio-kavanagh" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Turismo BA</a>; Contreras 2006).
          </p>
          <p>
            One quirk survives: the Kavanagh has no garages and no electric intercom. Visitors must announce themselves at reception and are phoned up to the apartment. ASCE describes it as one of the world's early reinforced-concrete skyscrapers with central A/C, twelve elevators and a deliberately slender structure (<a href="https://www.asce.org/about-civil-engineering/history-and-heritage/historic-landmarks/kavanagh-building" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">ASCE</a>). <em>Note on the A/C:</em> Contreras says the original central system stopped operating in 1960; later press dates its removal only recently. Both agree it no longer runs.
          </p>
          <p>
            At completion it surpassed Montevideo's Palacio Salvo (1928), São Paulo's Martinelli and every Argentine tower to become the tallest building in Latin America and the world's tallest reinforced-concrete structure. It held the Latin American record until 1947, when São Paulo's Altino Arantes (Banespa) building overtook it.
          </p>
          <p>
            Its plan included a basement, ground floor and 30 upper floors, with 102 apartments across six wings (A, B, C, E, F and G) in Contreras' detailed count, plus the rooftop <em>mirador</em> with an astronomical observatory. Floors 1–12 held six apartments each, floors 13–20 three each and the upper floors mostly one full-floor unit apiece. Floor 21 housed elevator machinery and the A/C plant; floor 30 held the water tanks. The largest unit was the 14th floor: a single ~700 m² apartment with three terraces, a library, study, multiple bedrooms each with a private bath and a bar-galley linking the wings.
          </p>
          <p>
            Stylistically it is usually labeled Rationalist / Modernist / Art Deco, but not doctrinaire modernism. Argentina's heritage office reads it as a hybrid of New York vertical Art Deco, French nautical metaphor and local Beaux-Arts tradition (<a href="https://www.argentina.gob.ar/capital-humano/cultura/monumentos/edificio-kavanagh" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Argentina.gob.ar</a>).
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="spite-legend" aria-labelledby="spite-legend-heading">
          <h2 id="spite-legend-heading">The spite legend and why it doesn't hold up</h2>
          <p>
            The standard tale says Corina fell for an Anchorena heir, that the family rejected the match as beneath them and that she retaliated by building a tower that blocked the Anchorenas' view from their palace to the Basílica del Santísimo Sacramento, their family church and mausoleum (<a href="https://turismo.buenosaires.gob.ar/en/otros-establecimientos/kavanagh-building" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Turismo BA: Kavanagh Building</a>). A more elaborate version has her waiting for matriarch <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mercedes_Castellanos_de_Anchorena" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Mercedes Castellanos de Anchorena</a> to leave on vacation, then buying the vacant lot by doubling the offer and telling the architects to obstruct the church from as many angles as possible.
          </p>
          <p>The story fractures under scrutiny:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Multiple incompatible variants exist. Some cast a <em>daughter</em> of Corina falling for an Anchorena son (or, per basilica staff, a chauffeur). A monument-commission researcher rejected these because Corina had no documented children (<a href="https://www.lanacion.com.ar/sociedad/la-majestuosa-basilica-retiro-quisieron-ocultar-amor-nid2190151/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">La Nación: La majestuosa basílica</a>).</li>
            <li>The chronology fails. Mercedes Castellanos de Anchorena died in 1920, over a decade before the Kavanagh was built; the palace was sold to the state in 1936 (<a href="https://www.lanacion.com.ar/sociedad/la-majestuosa-basilica-retiro-quisieron-ocultar-amor-nid2190151/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">La Nación</a>).</li>
            <li>Historian Daniel Balmaceda calls the Corina–<a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aar%C3%B3n_de_Anchorena" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Aarón de Anchorena</a> marriage-revenge story "fake," finding no evidence of any marriage project between them (<a href="https://www.lanacion.com.ar/la-nacion-revista/el-anchorena-aventurero-que-cruzo-el-rio-de-la-plata-en-globo-exploro-la-patagonia-y-fue-pionero-del-nid25102022/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">La Nación: El Anchorena aventurero</a>). Historians Roberto L. Elissalde, Diego Zigiotto and Mariela Blanco likewise find no documentary trace of the romance or the feud.</li>
            <li>Nougués adds an architectural problem for the revenge story. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alejandro_Bustillo" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Alejandro Bustillo</a> had designed a major Plaza Hotel expansion for the Tornquist group in 1928; had it been built, it would have blocked the basilica's sightline years before the Kavanagh existed. He also points to the economic absurdity: selling three estancias purely out of spite would have been madness ("<em>haber vendido tres estancias para hacerlo es una locura</em>").</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Contreras (2006) records another version of the legend: Corina, supposedly at odds with the Catholic Church, built the tower to block the view of the Basílica del Santísimo Sacramento from her <em>friend</em> Mercedes Castellanos de Anchorena, who had funded the church and lived in what is now the Foreign Ministry. He rejects that version on the same grounds. Some sources say Corina was never estranged from the Church, and Mercedes de Anchorena died around 1920, well before construction. The contradiction is revealing: some versions cast Mercedes as Corina's rival, others as her friend. That looks less like preserved memory than a motive reverse-engineered from the building's obvious geometry.
          </p>
          <p>
            The view-blocking effect is real. The revenge motive is unproven and probably mythologized. The legend endures because the urban geometry fits it perfectly: the basilica's front is now famously best seen from the narrow Pasaje Corina Kavanagh (<a href="https://www.lanacion.com.ar/sociedad/la-majestuosa-basilica-retiro-quisieron-ocultar-amor-nid2190151/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">La Nación</a>).
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="anchorena-side" aria-labelledby="anchorena-side-heading">
          <h2 id="anchorena-side-heading">The Anchorena side</h2>
          <p>
            The "spited" building is today Palacio San Martín (formerly Palacio Anchorena), built 1905–1909 by architect <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alejandro_Christophersen" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Alejandro Christophersen</a> for Mercedes Castellanos de Anchorena, with three residences. One was inhabited by Mercedes and her son Aarón. The Argentine state acquired it in 1936 for the Foreign Ministry (<a href="https://cancilleria.gob.ar/en/institutional/heritage/san-martin-palace" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Cancillería Argentina</a>). Mercedes Castellanos de Anchorena (born Rosario, 24 September 1840; a papal countess) died 9 July 1920 and rests in the crypt of the Basílica del Santísimo Sacramento, which she funded (designed by French architects Coulomb and Chauvet, consecrated 1916) (<a href="https://turismo.buenosaires.gob.ar/en/atractivo/bas%C3%ADlica-del-sant%C3%ADsimo-sacramento" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Turismo BA</a>). The supposed love interest, Aarón de Anchorena (1877–1965), was a celebrated bachelor-adventurer, balloonist, motorist and explorer. He married Zelmira Paz in Paris in 1933, with no record of any tie to Corina.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="after-completion" aria-labelledby="after-completion-heading">
          <h2 id="after-completion-heading">History after completion</h2>
          <p>
            The Kavanagh opened with a reputation for modern apartment living. It also entered literature and magazine culture: it appeared on the cover of <cite>Caras y Caretas</cite> and was written about by <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manuel_Mujica_Lainez" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Manuel Mujica Lainez</a>, <a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/H%C3%A9ctor_Viel_Temperley" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Héctor Viel Temperley</a> and <a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Esther_Cross" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Esther Cross</a> (<a href="https://www.lanacion.com.ar/cultura/los-secretos-del-kavanagh-el-primer-edificio-moderno-de-buenos-aires-nid2139269/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">La Nación: Los secretos del Kavanagh</a>).
          </p>
          <p>
            Under <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Juan_Per%C3%B3n" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Perón</a>'s first governments (1946–1955), the Kavanagh was attacked as a bastion of the landed aristocracy. Accounts say <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eva_Per%C3%B3n" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Evita</a> considered buying it, or even expropriating it, for workers. During the 1955 church burnings, some tried to set the building on fire. The attempt was reportedly stopped only because Perón's Secretary of Commerce lived there. When the taller Edificio Alas rose nearby, the two towers were pulled into political argument: the Kavanagh as an icon of the <em>oligarquía terrateniente</em>, the landed oligarchy, for Peronists, the Alas as an image of "the tyranny" for anti-Peronists (Contreras 2006).
          </p>
          <p>
            Over the decades, residents have included former economy minister <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jos%C3%A9_Alfredo_Mart%C3%ADnez_de_Hoz" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">José Alfredo Martínez de Hoz</a>, chef <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Mallmann" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Francis Mallmann</a>, journalists <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joaqu%C3%ADn_Morales_Sol%C3%A1" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Joaquín Morales Solá</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jorge_Lanata" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Jorge Lanata</a>, model <a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claudia_S%C3%A1nchez" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Claudia Sánchez</a>, <a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Torcuato_Di_Tella_%28hijo%29" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Torcuato Di Tella</a> (whose widow Tamara Di Tella still lives there), members of the Pérez Companc and Eskenazi families, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carlos_Corach" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Carlos Corach</a>, analyst <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carlos_Maslat%C3%B3n" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Carlos Maslatón</a> and impresario Leonardo Barujel (apt. 1°A). Through Barujel's flat passed <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maurice_Chevalier" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Maurice Chevalier</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Aznavour" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Charles Aznavour</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89dith_Piaf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Edith Piaf</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sammy_Davis_Jr." target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Sammy Davis Jr.</a> and others; fashion designer Roberto Devorik hosted <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Madonna" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Madonna</a> there during her Buenos Aires visit. Corina's 14 A penthouse later passed to the Roberts banking family and, around 2003–2007, to British-based multimillionaire Lord Alain Levenfiche (Contreras 2006; La Nación).
          </p>
          <p>
            The late arrival of horizontal-property law cost Corina her building. The Kavanagh was conceived as an <em>edificio de renta</em>: a single-owner income property whose value depended on rent. Two problems compounded. First, Argentina's rent-freeze laws of the 1940s locked nominal rents in place while inflation gutted their real value, strangling the income stream that justified holding the whole tower. Second, until Ley 13.512 (1948), there was no legal mechanism to subdivide a building's title and sell apartments individually. Argentina passed that reform later than Brazil (1928), Chile (1937) and Uruguay (1946).
          </p>
          <p>
            For years Corina was trapped. Her rental income was shrinking, and she had no way to raise capital by selling pieces of the asset. When by-unit sale finally became legal, selling the flats one at a time became the only exit. But she was liquidating a devalued asset under pressure in a market of protected sitting tenants. She ended up selling nearly every apartment (La Nación dates the atomization to 1949–1951), keeping only two units in wing C (floors 6 and 7) and losing much of her fortune in the process. She remained in the building until her death in 1984 (Contreras 2006; <a href="https://www.lanacion.com.ar/cultura/los-secretos-del-kavanagh-el-primer-edificio-moderno-de-buenos-aires-nid2139269/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">La Nación</a>).
          </p>

          <h3>Recognitions</h3>
          <p>Per Contreras (2006), who lists all four:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>1936: Municipal Prize for Collective Housing and Façade.</li>
            <li>1939: Honourable Mention from the American Institute of Architects (AIA).</li>
            <li>1994: ASCE International Historic Civil Engineering Landmark. Argentine media routinely place it alongside the Eiffel Tower, the Aswan Dam and the Panama Canal, but that comparison comes from secondary Argentine sources. ASCE's own citation instead says the tower rose in the 1930s when Argentina had one of the world's strongest economies (<a href="https://www.asce.org/about-civil-engineering/history-and-heritage/historic-landmarks/kavanagh-building" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">ASCE</a>).</li>
            <li>1999: Declared a Monumento Histórico Nacional by the Comisión Nacional de Museos y Monumentos in April 1999, formalized in Decree 349/1999 (<a href="https://servicios.infoleg.gob.ar/infolegInternet/anexos/55000-59999/57386/norma.htm" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">InfoLEG</a>).</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            A 2013 Clarín survey of 600 non-specialists chose it as the building most liked by porteños, Buenos Aires residents (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kavanagh_Building" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Wikipedia: Kavanagh Building</a>). Since 1999, the owners' consortium has run a phased façade restoration by Marcelo Magadán y Asociados, cleaning and consolidating the <em>símil piedra</em>, or stone-like, render with non-aggressive conservation. The work restored the original gradient in the render, which lightens from grey at the base to a chalky white near the top.
          </p>
          <p>
            The UNESCO claim is false. Contreras (2006), along with much tourism and press coverage, lists a 1999 recognition as "Patrimonio Mundial de la Arquitectura de la Modernidad en la lista de la UNESCO." There is no such UNESCO category. No designation called "World Heritage of Modern Architecture" exists, and the Kavanagh is not a UNESCO World Heritage Site (<a href="https://whc.unesco.org/en/statesparties/ar" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">UNESCO: Argentina</a>). Argentina's only UNESCO World Heritage properties are sites like Los Glaciares, Iguazú, the Jesuit Missions/Estancias, Península Valdés, Cueva de las Manos, Ischigualasto/Talampaya, Qhapaq Ñan and the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Le_Corbusier" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Le Corbusier</a> inscription (Curutchet House in La Plata), not the Kavanagh.
          </p>
          <p>
            What actually happened is simpler. In 1999 Argentina declared the Kavanagh a National Historic Monument, a domestic designation. Separately, DOCOMOMO (Documentation and Conservation of the Modern Movement) maintains registries of modernist buildings, and the Kavanagh appears on such lists. At some point, the national-monument declaration and/or a DOCOMOMO-type listing seems to have been conflated with "UNESCO" to make the recognition sound grander. The inflated claim then spread through guidebooks, tourism copy and even this heritage monograph. Treat every "UNESCO World Heritage" statement about the Kavanagh as incorrect.
          </p>
          <p>
            The myth has also spawned a secondary false claim: <cite>Las mil y una curiosidades de Buenos Aires</cite> (De los Cuatro Vientos, 2007) repeats the UNESCO story and adds that the distinction supposedly exempted the building's residents from municipal taxes. This is doubly wrong. The UNESCO designation itself is fictional, and no such tax exemption follows from any heritage listing. Owners in fact pay the standard municipal charges and, as a monument, face added preservation constraints.
          </p>
          <p>
            The building's only genuine top-tier recognitions are the Argentine National Historic Monument status (Decree 349/1999) and the ASCE International Historic Civil Engineering Landmark (1994).
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="present-day" aria-labelledby="present-day-heading">
          <h2 id="present-day-heading">Present day</h2>
          <p>
            The Kavanagh remains primarily a private residential building (~105 apartments), not a museum. It also has the practical problems of an old luxury tower: costly maintenance, no garages, no modern amenity package and heritage constraints. A 2025 Toribio Achával note claimed that roughly 30% of units were for sale, with high monthly expenses and prices from about US$260k to US$1M. That is broker commentary, not official building data (<a href="https://www.toribioachaval.com.ar/arquitectura-decoracion/edificio-kavanagh-leyenda-y-realidad-en-el-mercado-inmobiliario" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Toribio Achával</a>). The 14 A penthouse has been on and off the market for years, with its asking price falling from roughly US$7.9M in 2007 to under US$3M.
          </p>
          <p>
            In 2025, Cora Café opened in the ground-floor commercial area, in a former jewelry-store space, after a long approval process with the building's <em>consorcio</em>, or owners' association. It was the first gastronomic venture in the building and operates under restrictions, including no kitchen or open fire. The same reporting notes that the original central A/C system no longer operates and has been replaced by compact units that partly altered the façade composition (<a href="https://www.lanacion.com.ar/sabado/en-el-kavanagh-el-nuevo-cafe-que-rinde-homenaje-a-la-historia-del-edificio-nid03032025/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">La Nación: Cora Café</a>).
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="caveats" aria-labelledby="caveats-heading">
          <h2 id="caveats-heading">Caveats on conflicting figures</h2>
          <p>Sources disagree on several numbers because they use different counting conventions and imprecise secondary reporting:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Floors: 30, 31 or 32 (habitable vs. total, with/without the rooftop <em>mirador</em>).</li>
            <li>Apartments: cited as anywhere from 100 to 107; Contreras counts 102, most press says 105.</li>
            <li>Inauguration: 2, 3 or 15 January 1936 (the best-sourced date).</li>
            <li>Construction duration: ~14 months (structure) vs. ~20 months (clearing to finish); Contreras gives 20.</li>
            <li>Height: ~110 m to the roof vs. ~120.35 m to the mast tip.</li>
            <li>Corina's residence: whether she genuinely lived in 14 A long-term is contested; the most detailed account (Nougués) has her moving to smaller 6 C / 7 C units after her fortune shrank.</li>
            <li>Estancias sold: two (Contreras) vs. three in Venado Tuerto (Nougués/La Nación).</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            One recurring English-language error worth flagging: several sources garble the tale as "Kavanagh's <em>daughter</em>" falling for an Anchorena. The legend concerns Corina herself, who had no children.
          </p>
        </section>

